  "prompt": "Can a set be both a subset and a proper subset?",
  "response": "Yes, a set can be both a **subset** and a **proper subset**, but only under certain conditions.\n\n1. **Subset Definition**: A set \\( A \\) is a **subset** of a set \\( B \\) (denoted \\( A \\subseteq B \\)) if every element of \\( A \\) is also an element of \\( B \\).\n\n2. **Proper Subset Definition**: A set \\( A \\) is a **proper subset** of a set \\( B \\) (denoted \\( A \\subsetneq B \\)) if \\( A \\) is a subset of \\( B \\) and there exists at least one element in \\( B \\) that is not in \\( A \\).\n\n### Key Insight:\n- If \\( A \\) is a proper subset of \\( B \\), it must also be a subset of \\( B \\). However, the converse is not true unless \\( A \\neq B \\).\n\n### Example:\nLet \\( B = \\{1, 2, 3, 4\\} \\) and \\( A = \\{1, 2, 3\\} \\).\n\nYou can see that:\n- \\( A \\subseteq B \\) because every element of \\( A \\) is also an element of \\( B \\).\n- \\( A \\subsetneq B \\) because there is at least one element in \\( B \\) (the element \\( 4 \\)) that is not in \\( A \\).\n\nThus, \\( A \\) is both a **subset** and a **proper subset** of \\( B \\).\n\n### Special Case:\nIf \\( A = B \\), then \\( A \\) is a subset of \\( B \\) but **not** a proper subset.\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\text{A set can be both a subset and a proper subset if it is strictly contained within the larger set.}}\n\\]",
